			<div class="post-3091 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized" id="post-3091">
			<h2><a class="title" href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/10/07/my-favorite-teacher-william-hickey-part-1/" rel="bookmark">My Favorite Teacher: William Hickey &#8211; Part&nbsp;1~</a></h2>
			<div class="info">
				<span class="date">October 7, 2020</span>
				<span class="author"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/author/otoolefan/" title="Posts by OTOOLEFAN" rel="author">OTOOLEFAN</a></span>								<span class="comments"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/10/07/my-favorite-teacher-william-hickey-part-1/#respond">Leave a comment</a></span>
				<div class="fixed"></div>
			</div>
			<div class="content">
				
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="3093" data-permalink="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/10/07/my-favorite-teacher-william-hickey-part-1/ahickey/" data-orig-file="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg" data-orig-size="292,173" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="ahickey" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg?w=292" data-large-file="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg?w=292" src="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg?w=292" alt="" class="wp-image-3093" width="584" height="346" srcset="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg 292w, https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/ahickey.jpg?w=150 150w" sizes="(max-width: 584px) 100vw, 584px" /><figcaption>William Hickey in <em>Prizzi&#8217;s Honor </em>(1985)</figcaption></figure>



<p>By Don Millard</p>



<p></p>



<p>I&#8217;ve had some very good teachers and a few very bad teachers in my life. But there&#8217;s one teacher I had after all those who towers above the rest: Oscar nominated character actor William Hickey.  </p>



<p>When I first saw <em>Prizzi&#8217;s Honor </em>on, yes, VHS, in 1985, I would&#8217;ve never believed that just two years later William Hickey would be my acting teacher! Indeed, when I think about it now, I kind of have to rub my eyes and ask myself if it really happened. </p>



<p>It did.</p>



<p>When I watched <em>Prizzi&#8217;s Honor, </em>William Hickey&#8217;s bravura performance as the Mafia Don caught my eye. In my opinion, he stole every scene he was in&#8212;quite a feat for a film that starred Jack Nicholson, Angelica Huston, Kathleen Turner, and was directed by the great John Huston, whom Hickey had worked with before. I wasn&#8217;t surprised when I heard he was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor. He certainly had my vote. </p>



<p>But it was not to be. He would lose to Don Ameche, a sentimental choice by the Academy, probably because he had never won before, and this was likely his last chance. It seemed to me&#8211;and still does&#8211;that this was more of a lifetime achievement award than it was for his actual performance in <em>Trading Places. </em>I thought Hickey was robbed, frankly, and this was long before he was my teacher.</p>



<p>You probably know William Hickey best as crotchety old Uncle Lewis in <em>National Lampoon&#8217;s Christmas Vacation</em>, the same grumpy old man who torches the Griswold Christmas tree with his &#8220;stogie.&#8221; Hickey also used his unmistakable voice for the character Dr. Finkelstein in Tim Burton&#8217;s <em>The Nightmare Before Christmas</em>.</p>



<p>So, how on earth did he ever become my acting teacher?</p>



<p>Well, it was late May 1987, and I&#8217;d just come back from a nearly month long sojourn in Ireland, my second visit to that enchanted isle. It was almost exactly a year before that my mother had died from cancer. The doctors at Yale New Haven Hospital had found a malignant tumor on her sciatic nerve the day after I&#8217;d come back from my first vagabonding trip to the Ireland, Wales, England, Scotland, and Paris in June of 1985.</p>



<p>When I came home from being in Ireland for almost a month, I was at a real crosswords in my life. For starters, I wasn&#8217;t thrilled to be back in the good ol&#8217; U.S.A. Indeed, I found myself tearing up as I walked through JFK Airport, especially once I began hearing the harsh, nasal, discordant accent of my people again. Ugh. There were no lilting, musical brogues here&#8211;just the short, clipped staccato sounds of harried, disgruntled souls in a hurry.</p>



<p>I wasn&#8217;t looking forward to coming back to the empty house of heartbreak our home had become, either. My Mother was the glue that had always held our family together, and now that she was gone, my Dad and I had grown even farther apart, not closer, in our grief. Being adopted and an only child just made it all even worse, if that was possible. The emptiness that now filled our once happy home was asphyxiating. I  still remember coming across her old, black and silver cat glasses in a drawer months after her death and just sobbing. It&#8217;s always the little things that pierce your heart.</p>



<p>My Mom had always encouraged my artistic pursuits and told me I was talented, while my Dad thought maybe I should join the Army or something. </p>



<p>Once when I was still in high school and we were eating dinner, my Mom looked at me and said, approvingly: &#8220;He really looks like an artist.&#8221; My Dad looked up from his mashed potatoes with a grimace that told me he was worried that maybe I was gay.</p>



<p>Artistically, I had sort of built up a little body of work. I remember when I was a Junior in high school, I saw Cameron Crowe on, I swear, the Merv Griffin Show. He was on there talking about how he&#8217;d posed as a high school student so he could write a book about it, and how it was now going to be turned into a movie. This intrigued me, and inspired me to write a novel about my own high school that same year. Two of my actual teachers were raging alcoholics, and I remember giving them the character names Jack Yukon and Tom Collins. I&#8217;m sure it wasn&#8217;t the great American novel, but it was a good writing exercise for me and also fun. I titled it <em>The Horrible Hopefuls of Harding High</em>. I still have it.</p>



<p>During my first couple of weeks at Keene State College in New Hampshire, I wrote a short, light one act play I called <em>Adam Vs. Eve</em>. I submitted it to our college literary magazine a year later for the hell of it. It was accepted and published, with the editor telling me it was one of the best submissions they&#8217;d received that semester. It was a thrill to see something I&#8217;d written in my dorm room one evening in print! It made me feel like a real writer. I still have a copy of this, too.</p>



<p>I left college after my first semester as a Sophomore because I wanted to travel and have an adventure while I was still young. So many of my fellow classmates at Keene talked about all the places they were going to visit when they retired. I didn&#8217;t want to wait that long. I also felt that if I truly wanted to become a writer, I needed experiences, not classes. Furthermore, I believed that an English degree would be practically useless in my case since I had no desire to become a teacher. </p>



<p>After leaving college, I got a job with our local supermarket in order to save money for my big trip. My Dad even said he&#8217;d match whatever money I saved toward my sojourn. &#8220;He wants to have an adventure,&#8221; my Mom said. She always understood me. </p>



<p>I had started writing a screenplay not long after I left college and began working. I was almost done, too, but then I suddenly got stuck right before it was time for me to go bon voyage to Ireland, Britain, and France with one of my best friends from our neighborhood. </p>



<p>As I said, the day after I got back from Paris, we found out my Mother had cancer. I spent the next year talking her to all her chemotherapy and then radiation treatments. My Dad worked second shift at the postal terminal in New Haven, and couldn&#8217;t have taken all that time off. Besides, I wanted to be the one who took her to her treatments. I got to spend even more time with her and we grew even closer, if that was possible. She died in early June of 1986, almost a year to the day she was diagnosed. I would soon find out in the worst possible way that this is something you never get over, just learn to live with. I was able to finish my screenplay once I returned from my trip as well. This would be called <em>Dead Souls: A Drama of Inactivity.</em> It&#8217;s a dystopian satire on America; how everyone is stupid and just watches television to fill their empty lives. The hero was written with Peter O&#8217;Toole in mind.</p>



<p>I still have that, too, if you&#8217;re wondering.</p>



<p>I found myself suddenly writing again only a few weeks after her death. At first I thought it was just an extended monologue, but it soon grew into something else. It was a story about a young man very much like me who was venting his spleen about everything that pissed him off about life. Each chapter was a different subject. I guess it was like therapy, and an artistic way of dealing with my grief. It ended up being a novella, and I&#8217;d finish it that same terrible summer and call it <em>Rebel With A Cause: The Shocking Story Of A Young Man Who Gave Humanity The Finger!</em> </p>



<p>I still have it, too. The first two chapters can be found on this same site on here.</p>



<p>So, when I came back from Ireland in late Spring of 1987, I was determined to get out of the funk that had engulfed my soul since my Mother&#8217;s death. But how would I do that? Go back to college? No. I wanted to write a new chapter in my life! </p>



<p>But what would it be?</p>



<p></p>



<p>.</p>
