			<h2><a class="title" href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/10/01/my-visit-to-robert-louis-stevensons-house-by-don-millard/" rel="bookmark">My Visit To Robert Louis Stevenson&#8217;s House</a></h2>
			<div class="info">
				<span class="date">October 1, 2020</span>
				<span class="author"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/author/otoolefan/" title="Posts by OTOOLEFAN" rel="author">OTOOLEFAN</a></span>								<span class="comments"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/10/01/my-visit-to-robert-louis-stevensons-house-by-don-millard/#respond">Leave a comment</a></span>
				<div class="fixed"></div>
			</div>
			<div class="content">
				
<figure class="wp-block-image is-resized"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMvVxturnCT7b5L4RYccYzAXzGIrQZKb7P3Q23M=w325-h182-k-no" alt="Photo 2" width="370" height="208" /><figcaption><strong>Front door of Robert Louis Stevenson House  17 Heriot Row, Edinburgh</strong></figcaption></figure>



<p>By Don Millard</p>



<p>In the Spring of 1985, my friend Dave and I traveled abroad. We vagabonded around Ireland, Wales, England, Scotland, and then France, where we ran out of money in Paris, a little over a month later.  We flew home from Paris after about 4 nights in the City of Lights.</p>



<p>When we got into Scotland, I wasn&#8217;t prepared for how beautiful Edinburgh is, which made it that much more beautiful. It is still, all these years later, the most gorgeous city I&#8217;ve ever been in. While we were there, I remembered that one of my very favorite authors was from Edinburgh: Robert Louis Stevenson.<strong> The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll &amp; Mr. Hyde </strong>has  become part of our consciousness, not to mention the moody and lyrical <strong>KIDNAPPED</strong>, as well as the pure adventure of <strong>TREASURE ISLAND.</strong> I decided that we should try to find his house, so that we could say we&#8217;d seen it and had been there. </p>



<p><strong>I kept a journal during our trip to document it as best I could. The following is taken verbatim from that journal about our brush with Robert Louis Stevenson ~</strong></p>



<p>Dave and I found Heriot Row on our own. As we walked up the steps, there hung the sign &#8212;</p>



<p>                  <strong>Home Of Robert Louis Stevenson </strong></p>



<p>There was a sign under it which stated that it was a private home, not a museum.</p>



<p>I sat down on the steps anyway and began writing away in this book. I told Dave I just wanted to be able to say I wrote a passage in my journal while sitting on Robert Louis Stevenson&#8217;s steps. Dave was a bit unenthusiastic and satirical at first. He really didn&#8217;t want to hang around there.</p>



<p>&#8220;Well, here it is,&#8221; he said.</p>



<p>I was writing in my journal now and Dave began to do the same. We both had our backs to the door of Stevenson&#8217;s house. </p>



<p>After about ten minutes, while I was still writing, I heard the door behind me open. I expected trouble. I was sitting on someone&#8217;s steps and it was a private home, not a museum. After a few moments I turned around to face the music. When I turned around, I saw smiles instead! There was a middle-aged woman and a younger man standing in the doorway. </p>



<p>&#8220;Oh, are you writing in your little journals?&#8221; the woman said to Dave and me.</p>



<p>She was pushing a bicycle out of the door and she asked us our names and where we were from. When she heard my last name, she said,</p>



<p>&#8220;Millard?&#8221; like I was famous or something. The younger man was her son and he invited us into the house to have some tea. They were descendants of Robert Louis Stevenson!</p>



<p>Let me now just mention that only moments before we found Stevenson&#8217;s house, a tour bus pulled up next to one of the doors on Heriot Row. It lingered there for about 5 1/2 seconds and then moved on. I knew that was where Stevenson&#8217;s place must be.</p>



<p>The home inside was posh, elegant, and full of heirlooms. The man took our coats and then directed us into the dining room. </p>



<p>&#8220;Would you like some wine?&#8221; he said.</p>



<p>&#8220;Sure!&#8221; we said. </p>



<p>We were having tea at tea time and wine and cheese like we were celebrities! The man was funny and hospitable to us. He was also wearing an ascot.</p>



<p>We told him of our travels and the like. After we had drank our tea and wine and exhausted many subjects, the man said,</p>



<p>&#8220;Well, since this is a Stevenson shrine, let me show you around.&#8221;</p>



<p>This man&#8217;s appearance was quite striking. He had a perfect full-bodied red beard and his skin was incredibly unblemished. He looked like a portrait. Or a literary character. His appearance seemed perfect if you consider the setting. </p>



<p>We were then led into Robert Louis Stevenson&#8217;s bedroom. He apologized because the bed wasn&#8217;t made. I thought that perhaps that was the way Stevenson left it. </p>



<p>The tour was one of those great accidents of life. It reminded me of the time I got invited into James Dean&#8217;s house. </p>



<p>After the personal tour of the house, we laughed because of the tour bus and the two different worlds of traveling. </p>



<p>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8211;End of Entry&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</p>



<p>So glad I kept a journal of our trip! Some years later, I painted a portrait of Robert Louis Stevenson from a painting done by John Singer Sargent:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image is-resized"><img src="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/aaroblouie1.jpg?resize=219%2C219" alt="aaroblouie1" width="415" height="415" /><figcaption><strong>Portrait of Robert Louis Stevenson (after Sargent)</strong></figcaption></figure>



<div class="wp-block-file"><a href="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/10/aaroblouie1.jpg" class="wp-block-file__button" download>Download</a></div>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator" />



<p></p>



