			<div class="post-3052 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized" id="post-3052">
			<h2><a class="title" href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/09/27/a-season-in-hell-part-12/" rel="bookmark">A Season In Hell &#8211; Part 12&nbsp;~</a></h2>
			<div class="info">
				<span class="date">September 27, 2020</span>
				<span class="author"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/author/otoolefan/" title="Posts by OTOOLEFAN" rel="author">OTOOLEFAN</a></span>								<span class="comments"><a href="https://otoolefan.wordpress.com/2020/09/27/a-season-in-hell-part-12/#respond">Leave a comment</a></span>
				<div class="fixed"></div>
			</div>
			<div class="content">
				
<p>by Don Millard</p>



<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile">
<figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img class="wp-image-3054" src="https://otoolefan.files.wordpress.com/2020/09/bbnorthcarolina22-1.jpg?w=244" alt="" /></figure>
<div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<p class="has-large-font-size">Â </p>
</div>
</div>



<p>&nbsp;</p>



<p>It was in the early days of Spring 1995 that I prepared to make my getaway&#8211;yet again&#8211;from the Sunshine State. As my favorite comedian that I ever worked with, Frankie Bastille, said, &#8220;Florida is an old Spanish word that means tee shirt shop.&#8221;</p>



<p>By leaving when I did, I would miss all or nearly all of Winter in Virginia. My Mother&#8217;s house was at the foot of Hankey Mountain, and the region itself was surrounded by the Blue Ridge and Allegheny Mountains, so old man Winter can get pretty mean. I wanted to make my re-entry into the real world of four seasons as gentle as I could.</p>



<p>It would be a journey of nearly a thousand miles from Florida to Virginia, and I&#8217;d be driving every mile of it in my silver two seated car with the engine in the back.</p>



<p>The engine wouldn&#8217;t be the only thing in the back. Just a few weeks before I&#8217;d had a trailer hitch installed. I was very surprised at first that this was even possible, considering the size of my car.</p>



<p>This trailer hitch allowed me to turn my 1986 Toyota MR2 into a tug boat and to tow the remnants of my life behind me in the world&#8217;s smallest UHAUL trailer.</p>



<p>Though this UHAUL trailer was very small, it was plenty big enough to house what was left of my life with room to spare.</p>



<p>So, I&#8217;d be leaving Florida again&#8211;this time for Virginia, the land of my birth, the &#8220;Breadbasket of the Confederacy&#8221;, and the site of my biological father&#8217;s original sin of leaving my Mother at the altar knowing she was pregnant with me. I would be heading North to get to the South.</p>



<p>I went to see my Father the evening before I was to leave Florida&#8211;not knowing when or if I&#8217;d ever return.</p>



<p>We soon ran out of things to say to each other and it was time for me to go. As we were hugging goodbye in the driveway, my Dad said that I must be very happy to be going to live in Virginia and get to spend so much time with my Mother. He said he was happy for me and I know he meant it. He was a good man and had a good heart.</p>



<p>As I slowly walked back to my car, already half loaded down, tears suddenly welled up within me and I was overcome with emotion. I&#8217;m sure my Dad had no idea I was crying.</p>



<p>It wasn&#8217;t that I was wasn&#8217;t happy to be leaving Florida and going to Virginia&#8211;I was. Truly. What was making me cry was the awful feeling that I still wasn&#8217;t in control of my life. I was sad because I knew I hadn&#8217;t made this decision to go to Virginia solely because it was what I wanted to do. I couldn&#8217;t still help but wonder what I&#8217;d be doing had what happened to me in 1989 not happened to me. If I hadn&#8217;t got sick, what would I really be doing? Would there be someone by my side?</p>



<p>This question haunted and vexed me to my core as I tried to dry my eyes on the ride &#8220;home&#8221; to spend my very last night in the apartment across the Caloosahatchie River in Fort Myers.</p>



<p>I still felt like my world was off its axis. I tried to push these thoughts out of my head as best I could like always. But I finally felt like I at least had a choice again in my life and I had chosen. My choice would definitely bring some meaning back in my life. I didn&#8217;t want to remain adrift in Florida, drowning in a sea of heartache and humidity, spending my days at a meaningless job and evading back rubs from a creepy roommate in a cultural wasteland.</p>



<p>My Mother had told me that one of the first things Frank said to her about me was: &#8220;Now, Cuz, I&#8217;m gonna tell you right now&#8211;he&#8217;s a real city slicker, so don&#8217;t ever expect him to ever come live around here. But he&#8217;s one of the nicest young men I&#8217;ve ever met. You&#8217;ll be very proud.&#8221;</p>



<p>Maybe it was time for me to think about what my Mother needed&#8230; Maybe I could be a buffer between the hardness and cruelty she&#8217;d endured and was still enduring. Maybe, just maybe, despite my own condition, I could help her at least half as much as she&#8217;d already helped me. Maybe&#8230;</p>



<p>There&#8217;s one incident in particular I still wish I could bleach from my memory even as I write this now. When my Mother first told me about it over the phone, it made me not want to come to Virginia, but it also made me feel like I had to come to Virginia.</p>



<p>My Mom said she was cooking dinner for her and my half brother and half sister. She was opening a can of corned beef&#8211;the kind with the screw&#8211;when her hand slipped, causing her to slice her thumb open. When she told her kids what happened and asked for them to take her to the emergency room, they replied: &#8220;There&#8217;s the phone. Call 9-1-1.&#8221;</p>



<p>&#8220;It bled awful,&#8221; she said.</p>



<p>So, she bandaged her own thumb while these two vile creatures just sat there waited for their dinner to be ready.</p>



<p>A couple of hours later, after these two monsters had got their bellies full and left, my Mom drove herself and her crudely bandaged thumb to an urgent care center where she had to get her thumb stitched up. She would have a scar on that thumb for the rest of her life.</p>



<p>After she told me this story, I literally wanted to horsewhip those two. As I write now, it&#8217;s been over 20 years since this happened, and I still want to horsewhip them both for this right fucking now. I would bet houses that those two are Trump supporters now.</p>



<p>My hope for those two is best expressed by the late, great Sam Kinison: &#8220;I hope you slide under a gas truck and taste your own blood.&#8221;</p>



<p>The greatest challenge I&#8217;d face on this journey&#8211;besides the volume of miles&#8211;would be hauling the artifacts of my life behind me in that metal trailer without mishap or worse. The vital thing for me to remember, I kept telling myself, was to never forget that reverse was not an option. I literally could not back up. Period. I had to always stop or park in such a way that I could go forward again. If I screwed up, I had to get out of the car, uncouple the trailer&#8211;you get the idea. Don&#8217;t get me wrong, this mode of transportation was a zillion times better than being on a Greyhound Bus&#8211;not to mention that, unlike when you&#8217;re on a Greyhound, I would actually be speeding toward my destination the whole time.</p>



<p>Although my car was very little with not much room for anything, it was fully stocked with the two things I needed most to complete this drive: music and cigarettes. My car had a good stereo and the cassette player had been blaring my music since the day I got it in 1987. Its lone passenger seat where Jon Stewart, Billy Gardell, Steve Harvey, Rita Rudner, Tim Allen, and Paula Poundstone had all once sat was now a pile of cassettes, maps, and cigarette packs. Thank Zeus that this car was so mechanically sound, as my idea of maintenance back then was to put gas in it.</p>



<p>It was morning and time to leave.</p>



<p>As I said goodbye to my now ex-roommate Ralph in the parking lot, I mustered up enough phony sincerity to make an Evangelist proud. I&#8217;m absolutely sure that Ralph had no idea just how much I loathed him. I&#8217;m also certain that he thought he&#8217;d been a good influence on my life&#8230; That&#8217;s always the way it is with people. Creeps have no idea how creepy they are&#8211;it&#8217;s one of the things that makes them creeps.</p>



<p>As I slowly and carefully pulled away from Ralph and the apartment complex of the eternal car alarm, I found myself quietly ecstatic. I cranked Van Morrison up, lit a cigarette, and got on the highway, heading North to go South.</p>



<p>As the miles rolled by in fifth gear, I still had to remind myself that that metal trailer behind me was attached to me and my little puddle jumper. I had to remember I was now essentially two or more car lengths long, and to never dart in and out of a lane&#8211;or anywhere, for that matter. It was very stressful.</p>



<p>My plan was to push myself and try to make it as far as I could the first day so that the second day would be much easier and shorter to my Mother&#8217;s house in Virginia. Van Morrison, John Mellencamp, caffeine, and nicotine helped propel toward the Old Dominion. Having to stop for gas was always tricky, but I managed to not trap myself and was always able to pull forward and back on the highway.</p>



<p>After about ten or eleven hours of driving and smoking, I made it all the way to the state line of North Carolina. Sorry, Pedro, but I wasn&#8217;t about to stay at South of the Border again&#8211;those days were long gone&#8211;like most of Pedro&#8217;s buildings. I was happy with myself, as I&#8217;d already made about two thirds of my journey and I could stop for the night. It was 9 o&#8217;clock in the evening now. I was done.</p>



<p>Funny enough, I pulled into the nearly empty parking lot of the very same cheap, seedy motel I&#8217;d stayed at before when I&#8217;d driven to Virginia in the summer. I can&#8217;t remember the name of it, but I do remember the outside of the buildings were painted a sickly green. It&#8217;s best feature&#8211;besides being cheap&#8211;was that it was almost as close to the highway as a rest area.</p>



<p>As I got out of my car and stretched, I was hit with beautiful, non-humid cold air. It was heavenly. I went into the office and paid for a room. When I got in my room, it was just as dark and dank as I remembered&#8211;it may have even been the same room! I immediately turned the tv on so I wouldn&#8217;t feel alone. I was glad I&#8217;d picked up a 40 ounce bottle of beer the last time I&#8217;d put gas in my car. It would help me unwind and decompress, maybe even help me get to sleep. I was wired and exhausted at the same time.</p>



<p>As I laid out on the bed, looked around this room and drank it all in, a couple of lines from Tom Waits&#8217; spoken word song &#8220;9th &amp; Hennepin&#8221; came to mind:Â </p>
<p>Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  <em>And all the rooms they smell like diesel</em></p>
<p>Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  <em>And you take on the dreams of the ones who have slept here</em></p>



